or just squatting, an influx
of gangs and criminal

18:01.013 --> 18:04.383
organizations, the area
soon slipped into anarchy.

18:04.384 --> 18:09.321
There's a saying around here.

18:09.322 --> 18:11.157
Okay?

18:11.158 --> 18:14.826
This building's been hijacked.

18:14.827 --> 18:16.995
Everything that could
go wrong, did.

18:16.996 --> 18:20.466
People make a living
from different things.

18:20.467 --> 18:22.234
Some hurt people
to make a living.

18:22.235 --> 18:24.002
Some they sell their bodies.

18:24.003 --> 18:25.504
Sometimes things aren't always

18:25.505 --> 18:28.474
according to what you plan.

18:28.475 --> 18:29.808
This is where I live.

18:29.809 --> 18:36.215
This is where my life is.

18:36.216 --> 18:42.388
I'll show you.

18:42.389 --> 18:45.691
We talk down the street and
one of the many enterprises

18:45.692 --> 18:47.259
doing business on corners and in

18:47.260 --> 18:51.197
doorways around us becomes
alarmed at the sight of our

18:51.198 --> 18:51.431
cameras.

18:51.432 --> 18:55.834
Soon there's a mob of very
angry people coming our way.

18:55.835 --> 19:00.439
We do not turn around our
cameras for obvious reasons.

19:00.440 --> 19:06.345
These days things are
slowly, slowly improving.

19:06.346 --> 19:08.914
But before, we wouldn't
walk this freely.

19:08.915 --> 19:10.216
Now we are free.

19:10.217 --> 19:12.884
There's actual law enforcement
going on in fits and

19:12.885 --> 19:13.119
starts.

19:13.120 --> 19:16.222
And that's making a difference.

19:16.223 --> 19:19.958
Black owned legitimate
businesses have gained a real

19:19.959 --> 19:20.727
foothold.

19:20.728 --> 19:22.794
There are new revitalization

19:22.795 --> 19:26.031
projects like farmer's
markets springing up.

19:26.032 --> 19:27.466
Buildings are being reclaimed.

19:27.467 --> 19:32.571
And people here hope that
Hillbrow is past the bad old

19:32.572 --> 19:32.772
days.

19:32.773 --> 19:34.273
There's no fear now.

19:34.274 --> 19:35.807
You have to relax.

19:35.808 --> 19:38.211
Nothing will happen to you.

20:34.601 --> 20:36.935
>What's in a name?

20:36.936 --> 20:39.271
If the name is Soweto, you best

20:39.272 --> 20:45.711
believe it means plenty.

20:45.712 --> 20:46.945
This is Madu.

20:46.946 --> 20:48.714
For over a decade he's been in

20:48.715 --> 20:50.316
what has at times been the very

20:50.317 --> 20:52.851
difficult business
of driving a taxi.

20:52.852 --> 20:53.786
You should probably know that

20:53.787 --> 20:56.221
the word taxi in Soweto means

20:56.222 --> 21:02.661
something a little different
than, say, New York.

21:02.662 --> 21:07.399
How many taxis do
you have in Soweto?

21:07.400 --> 21:10.636
This coming from a particular
passenger means Soweto.

21:10.637 --> 21:12.237
Also this and this.

21:12.238 --> 21:15.341
Johannesburg has an elaborate
system of hand signals

21:15.342 --> 21:17.676
indicating desired
routes of travel.

21:17.677 --> 21:20.346
You're looking at the hand

21:20.347 --> 21:21.347
signals and say I'm not going

21:21.348 --> 21:22.248
there, I'm not going there.

21:22.249 --> 21:24.282
I'm looking at hand sayingals.

21:24.283 --> 21:31.990
In 1994 Soweto came into
being as workers lodging.

21:31.991 --> 21:33.992
A place to put black laborers

21:33.993 --> 21:35.527
comfortably removed
from white society.

21:35.528 --> 21:36.095
A ghetto.

21:36.096 --> 21:37.863
By the 1950s it had become the

21:37.864 --> 21:40.599
center of resistance
to white rule.

21:40.600 --> 21:41.767
Synonymous with the struggle

21:41.768 --> 21:48.207
against the whole
rotten racist system.

22:28.214 --> 22:34.586
Now there is a definite carhe

22:34.587 --> 22:36.287
to having lived in Soweto.

22:36.288 --> 22:37.789
A very real pride back at being

22:37.790 --> 22:38.990
in the center of things when it

22:38.991 --> 22:40.592
was hard and dangerous
to have an opinion.

22:40.593 --> 22:43.228
Nelson Mandela lived here.

22:43.229 --> 22:44.496
Desmond tutu.

22:44.497 --> 22:45.764
When you're of certain age and

22:45.765 --> 22:47.599
you say you were born and bred

22:47.600 --> 22:49.401
in Soweto, it means something.

22:49.402 --> 22:51.603
Do mostly people own
their homes or rent?

22:51.604 --> 22:53.739
Mostly people own their homes.

22:53.740 --> 22:55.240
Things start to get
a little better.

22:55.241 --> 22:56.341
Can you build up?

22:56.342 --> 22:57.342
You can build up.

22:57.343 --> 22:58.444
Look at the streets here and

22:58.445 --> 22:59.845
you see what that
kind of pride does.

22:59.846 --> 23:02.748
It may not be a rich area,
but it's immaculate.

23:02.749 --> 23:03.416
Squared away.

23:03.417 --> 23:05.150
An emerging middle class coming

23:05.151 --> 23:13.151
up, rather than
fleeing to elsewhere.

23:21.768 --> 23:23.635
You know where
you're going, right?

23:23.636 --> 23:24.136
Yeah.

23:24.137 --> 23:29.475
I know where I'm going.

23:29.476 --> 23:31.376
Next exit?

23:31.377 --> 23:33.311
Smoky delicious meat over flame.

23:33.312 --> 23:35.981
Under the overpass, all sorts of

23:35.982 --> 23:37.516
mystery meats for sale.

23:37.517 --> 23:39.518
The taxi man's lunch.

23:39.519 --> 23:44.490
We order some brisket,
some sausage, some heart.

23:44.491 --> 23:45.491
Beautiful thing.

23:45.492 --> 23:47.794
Meat, a cutting board, a knife.

23:59.005 --> 23:59.405
You chose well.

23:59.406 --> 24:07.406
These guys are good.

24:10.349 --> 24:11.349
♪

24:13.385 --> 24:14.753
Here, spread over thousands

24:14.754 --> 24:19.224
of square feet, the remnants
of white colonial rule.

24:19.225 --> 24:21.392
What's left from the descendants

24:21.393 --> 24:22.861
of Bible thumping Dutch settlers

24:22.862 --> 24:24.696
who came here to farm, to ranch,

24:24.697 --> 24:29.367
to build their own world
on top of an existing one.

24:29.368 --> 24:31.436
They came in the 1600s.

24:31.437 --> 24:32.538
If nothing else can be said

24:32.539 --> 24:35.907
about them, they
were a tough bunch.

24:35.908 --> 24:38.176
In the 1800s the British came.

24:38.177 --> 24:39.878
Diamonds were discovered.

24:39.879 --> 24:41.379
Greed heads jockeyed for power.

24:41.380 --> 24:43.715
There was war, and an ugly one.

24:43.716 --> 24:46.117
In the end there was an
uneasy shares of power.

24:46.118 --> 24:50.421
The boars been known
as Afrikaners.

24:50.422 --> 24:54.726
In the 20th century racist
Afrikaners ideology grew.

24:54.727 --> 24:56.628
Ar par tide was enacted.

24:56.629 --> 25:00.899
White domination because the
rule for almost 100 years.

25:00.900 --> 25:01.701
But look.

25:01.701 --> 25:01.901
Meat.

25:01.902 --> 25:05.737
You want to see an ex-pat south

25:05.738 --> 25:08.073
African weep, wave some
of this under their nose.

25:08.074 --> 25:10.408
It's like a Mussolini
themed restaurant?

25:10.409 --> 25:10.743
Yeah.

25:10.743 --> 25:11.243
That's it.

25:11.244 --> 25:13.311
That's it.

25:13.312 --> 25:14.479
Neofascist butchery.

25:14.480 --> 25:15.781
In the good old days.

25:15.782 --> 25:18.550
Doesn't look like any
butcher I've been into.

25:18.551 --> 25:22.888
Our north of northwest by
Johannesburg is Pretoria.

25:22.889 --> 25:24.790
Still the administrative
center of South Africa.

25:24.791 --> 25:27.926
Once the heart of apartheid.

25:27.927 --> 25:31.597
Here you can find a father/son

25:31.598 --> 25:33.231
butchery, restaurant
and themed museum.

25:33.232 --> 25:35.066
I just don't know how I
feel about this place.

25:35.067 --> 25:39.437
It doesn't fit in with my white

25:39.438 --> 25:41.907
liberal guilt sensibility.

25:41.908 --> 25:45.476
It just wouldn't be accepted.

25:45.477 --> 25:45.845
Couldn't exist.

25:45.846 --> 25:49.280
As any south African butcher

25:49.281 --> 25:53.685
would, they sprinkle salt,
brown sugar, more vinegar.

25:53.686 --> 25:55.654
Pack in layers, repeat.

25:55.655 --> 25:59.625
After 24 hours remove and
hang to air dry for a week.

25:59.626 --> 25:59.826
Voila.

25:59.827 --> 26:06.431
A tasty jerky treat we
can all get behind.

26:06.432 --> 26:09.635
Chef Andrea Burgener, south

26:09.636 --> 26:11.302
African by birth, English and

26:11.303 --> 26:12.671
German by background, with

26:12.672 --> 26:15.206
usually be found in the trenches

26:15.207 --> 26:18.677
of her Joburg restaurant,
the leopard.

26:18.678 --> 26:22.714
She's known for her playful
menus but loathes culinary

26:22.715 --> 26:22.949
fashion.

26:22.950 --> 26:26.384
She strives for a locally
grounded cuisine.

26:26.385 --> 26:27.686
Today, she's my guide
through this twilight zone.

26:27.687 --> 26:31.022
♪

26:31.023 --> 26:32.023
It's weird here.

26:32.024 --> 26:33.825
And though I'm told the place

26:33.826 --> 26:35.226
usually reflects the changing

26:35.227 --> 26:43.227
demographic of modern south
Africa, today, not so much.

26:45.337 --> 26:53.337
The customers may or may not
have feelings about the

26:53.412 --> 26:55.180
Afrikaner memorabilia.

26:55.181 --> 26:56.915
Really they just come for meat.

26:56.916 --> 27:00.351
Choose t-bone, rum steak.

27:00.352 --> 27:06.224
Spicy sausage made
from beef and pork.

27:06.225 --> 27:08.994
Our secret ingredient
is monkey gland sauce.

27:08.995 --> 27:11.196
Every steak house has
monkey gland sauce.

27:11.197 --> 27:12.197
It's barbecue sauce.

27:12.198 --> 27:13.665
They cook it up along with

27:13.666 --> 27:15.500
some pap and fries and presto.

27:15.501 --> 27:19.437
A colon clogging pile of
meat in the ruins of empire.

27:19.438 --> 27:19.872
Yeah.

27:19.873 --> 27:23.875
I mean, meat is a
very big thing.

27:23.876 --> 27:25.076
There's enough of it, I think.

27:25.077 --> 27:25.577
Good lord.

27:25.578 --> 27:28.213
I can swim in it.

27:28.214 --> 27:29.881
Tastes like oppression.

27:29.882 --> 27:33.184
After this show airs, I'm
going to get a huge amount of

27:33.185 --> 27:36.221
mail says why didn't
you go to Capetown?

27:36.222 --> 27:37.723
Great modern restaurants.

27:37.724 --> 27:38.457
Cutting edge chefs.

27:38.458 --> 27:40.425
Is it all right I
missed all that?

27:40.426 --> 27:42.861
I feel like those particular

27:42.862 --> 27:45.764
restaurants in Capetown are not

27:45.765 --> 27:46.598
really representative of what

27:46.599 --> 27:48.633
most people in this
country are eating.

27:48.634 --> 27:50.902
I think a lot of our most basic

27:50.903 --> 27:52.938
stuff is really what we do best.

27:52.939 --> 27:57.042
This food is absolutely got
no interest in fashion.

27:57.043 --> 27:58.810
It's never going to change.

27:58.811 --> 28:02.748
There'll still be the
monkey gland sauce.

28:02.749 --> 28:04.783
You think the white chefs
here understand the greatest

28:04.784 --> 28:07.218
advantage they have is that this

28:07.219 --> 28:13.091
enormous pan African larder of

28:13.092 --> 28:14.793
ingredients and flavors?

28:14.794 --> 28:15.061
No.

28:15.062 --> 28:16.294
If you're a whitey in the city

28:16.295 --> 28:17.428
you're probably going to eat the

28:17.429 --> 28:19.831
worst food of anyone in
the city, quite honestly.

28:19.832 --> 28:21.933
In every country, obviously
food is political.

28:21.934 --> 28:25.570
It always feels like it's a
bit more political here.

28:25.571 --> 28:26.938
That there are these layers of

28:26.939 --> 28:29.407
things that you couldn't have.

28:29.408 --> 28:30.242
Like restaurants.

28:30.243 --> 28:31.642
I go to restaurants.

28:31.643 --> 28:33.611
I think to myself, wow, this

28:33.612 --> 28:34.913
many years ago, I couldn't have

28:34.914 --> 28:36.281
come here with this person.

28:36.282 --> 28:39.017
They were not allowed
to sit in here.

28:39.018 --> 28:40.819
And I remember very
clearly being around 8.

28:40.820 --> 28:43.789
The cafe owner would regularly

28:43.790 --> 28:47.793
not pay the customer who
was black with change.

28:47.794 --> 28:49.761
He would pay him
with bubble gum.

28:49.762 --> 28:54.032
And the guy somehow,
he couldn't argue.

28:54.033 --> 28:57.468
If you were a black guy, you got

28:57.469 --> 29:00.171
your change in bubble gum.

29:00.172 --> 29:02.774
I was 8 years old feeling like,

29:02.775 --> 29:04.442
oh, my god, it was so terrible.

29:04.443 --> 29:05.844
But you couldn't say anything.

29:05.845 --> 29:10.949
Because that would
have been worse.

29:10.950 --> 29:13.451
It represented such badness.

29:13.452 --> 29:16.755
It just seems mad.

29:46.986 --> 29:48.519
>This is an elan.

29:48.520 --> 29:51.656
The largest antelope
in the world.

29:51.657 --> 29:59.657
It is also, unluckily
for him, delicious.

30:03.169 --> 30:07.505
[ Gunshots ]

30:07.506 --> 30:15.280
Got him.

30:15.281 --> 30:19.684
I think that was very good.

30:19.685 --> 30:21.953
It's a little sad.

30:21.954 --> 30:23.188
You know what?

30:23.189 --> 30:24.722
That is such good meat.

30:24.723 --> 30:29.260
That's really what we do.

30:29.261 --> 30:35.133
Though this one weighs in
around a ton, rest assured,

30:35.134 --> 30:40.238
every bite, every
scrap, will be eaten.

30:40.239 --> 30:44.575
Some of that, tonight at dinner.

30:44.576 --> 30:48.479
Chef Andrea Burgener, Dionne, a

30:48.480 --> 30:52.884
local hunting expert, and myself

30:52.885 --> 30:55.820
join Prospero Bailey
on his game farm.

30:55.821 --> 31:00.725
His dad was the legendary
publisher of the slyly

31:00.726 --> 31:01.427
subversive magazine.

31:01.428 --> 31:03.494
A black oriented investigative

31:03.495 --> 31:08.900
magazine slickly disguised
as glossy pop culture.

31:08.901 --> 31:10.969
Prospera's farm is mere 20
miles from Johannesburg.

31:10.970 --> 31:16.007
You see the city there?

31:16.008 --> 31:17.242
Yeah.

31:17.243 --> 31:18.776
To have all this in
sight of the city.

31:18.777 --> 31:21.746
Near his farm and hidden
within the city's shadow is

31:21.747 --> 31:24.916
what's known as the
cradle of humankind.

31:24.917 --> 31:27.252
A UNESCO world heritage site.

31:27.253 --> 31:28.486
An incredible look back at where

31:28.487 --> 31:36.487
we, the human animal, came from.

31:37.096 --> 31:39.030
It's a classic little sink hole.

31:39.031 --> 31:39.966
There are loads of these.

31:39.967 --> 31:41.632
This is what this area is.

31:41.633 --> 31:42.334
The cradle.

31:42.335 --> 31:43.601
It's called a cradle.

31:43.602 --> 31:46.037
Now a world heritage site.

31:46.038 --> 31:47.205
Because 60% of all the evidence

31:47.206 --> 31:49.607
for human evolution comes
out of the valley.

31:49.608 --> 31:51.943
It's from caves like this
that keep the record.

31:51.944 --> 31:56.114
That geology just conspires
to preserve fossils.

31:56.115 --> 31:58.116
They're very, very rare things.

31:58.117 --> 31:59.018
But they're found more here in

31:59.019 --> 32:02.387
the last ten years than
they're found anywhere.

32:02.388 --> 32:03.022
So you're home.

32:03.023 --> 32:04.289
This is where you started.

32:04.290 --> 32:06.224
This is my ancestral homeland?

32:06.225 --> 32:11.263
This is your ancestral homeland.

32:12.131 --> 32:17.103
♪

32:20.672 --> 32:23.674
That sound makes me happy.

32:23.675 --> 32:25.743
What does that sound
remind you of, guys?

32:25.744 --> 32:33.744
What does that evoke
for you, that sound?

32:36.388 --> 32:36.655
Prime evil.

32:36.656 --> 32:43.361
Your enemy's genitals
frying in hot oil?

32:43.362 --> 32:43.895
Nothing?

32:43.896 --> 32:45.263
I get to work on the heart.

32:45.264 --> 32:46.731
Something I strongly
suspect will be delicious.

32:46.732 --> 32:47.566
And I'm right.

32:47.567 --> 32:50.035
Andrea works her
magic on the liver.

32:50.036 --> 32:54.339
Dredged in flour and sauteed.

32:54.340 --> 32:57.842
This loin seared and
glazed with booze.

32:57.843 --> 33:00.911
There's elan papricash.

33:00.912 --> 33:04.715
A riff on the Hungarian stew
with paprika, peppers,

33:04.716 --> 33:10.855
onion, tomatoes and cream.

33:10.856 --> 33:15.026
As the sunsets over the belt,

33:15.027 --> 33:17.728
Johannesburg lights blinking
in the distance, a feast.

33:17.729 --> 33:18.963
Meat on the plate.

33:18.964 --> 33:22.300
Blood on my pants.

33:22.301 --> 33:22.901
Life is good.

33:22.902 --> 33:26.537
I've been very, very, very
confused by my visit here.

33:26.538 --> 33:31.609
You've got basically
a goulash here.

33:31.610 --> 33:34.445
The bread someone referred
to as Portuguese?

33:34.446 --> 33:34.813
Yep.

33:34.814 --> 33:38.983
Portuguese but it's from Madera.

33:38.984 --> 33:40.218
That bread.

33:40.219 --> 33:40.919
Flat bread.

33:40.920 --> 33:45.556
South Africa depending on who
I talk to is a completely

33:45.557 --> 33:46.724
different construct.

33:46.725 --> 33:48.293
So some people someone who comes

33:48.294 --> 33:49.727
from somewhere else in Africa

33:49.728 --> 33:50.928
and brings good stuff with them.

33:50.929 --> 33:54.399
Other people Malaysia, east
Indyes, Dutch, English

33:54.400 --> 33:54.900
influence.

33:54.901 --> 34:01.172
There were so many different
colonials colonialists.

34:01.173 --> 34:04.275
One at this table is originally
African and does that

34:04.276 --> 34:05.843
have a meaning?

34:05.844 --> 34:09.447
This wood is pine.

34:09.447 --> 34:14.485
I arrived in this country
spectacularly ignorant.

34:14.485 --> 34:18.724
I will leave
spectacularly ignorant.

34:36.108 --> 34:36.942
>Ramadan.

34:36.943 --> 34:40.210
At this hour, all
over Johannesburg.

34:40.212 --> 34:43.447
Members of South Africa's
sizable Muslim community

34:43.449 --> 34:43.681
observe.

34:43.683 --> 34:46.184
The religion of Islam as well as

34:46.185 --> 34:50.455
many of South Africa's most
beloved and most delicious

34:50.456 --> 34:52.822
dishes and ingredients like

34:52.824 --> 34:54.958
sambal, cutny and bunny chow

34:54.960 --> 34:59.564
come from Malaysia,
Indonesia, India.

34:59.565 --> 35:02.600
During apartheid many south
Africans would have been

35:02.601 --> 35:04.001
referred to as colored.

35:04.002 --> 35:04.970
Colored didn't mean black.

35:04.971 --> 35:07.071
It meant everybody else
who wasn't exactly white.

35:07.072 --> 35:11.008
Asians and mixed race.

35:11.009 --> 35:15.646
It's garlic, ginger
and chil chiles.

35:15.647 --> 35:18.383
In the observatory
neighborhood of Johannesburg,

35:18.384 --> 35:22.587
the Rasdian family prepares for

35:22.588 --> 35:26.824
the meal at sundown when
fasting for Ramadan is broken.

35:26.825 --> 35:31.662
Joey is a standup comedian, an

35:31.663 --> 35:35.032
actor of cape Malay background.

35:35.033 --> 35:39.837
This dish, panang curry
with beef and eggs.

35:39.838 --> 35:45.343
Joey's wife, Cindy,
prepares a chicken pie.

35:45.344 --> 35:52.217
Son, Hakeem, makes the
traditional Ramadan shake.

35:52.218 --> 35:57.088
Daughter, Laya.

35:59.358 --> 36:00.559
♪

36:02.961 --> 36:07.398
Everything smells terrific.

36:07.399 --> 36:08.533
That's soup.

36:08.534 --> 36:10.235
It's nicer to have soup after

36:10.236 --> 36:13.037
you've not eaten the whole day.

36:13.038 --> 36:14.705
It's light and nourishing and

36:14.706 --> 36:16.874
filling and all of
those good things.

36:16.875 --> 36:24.875
There's also cheese
and beef yes, I was.

36:26.318 --> 36:30.555
So how are things?

36:30.556 --> 36:32.590
It depends on what you
are speaking about.

36:32.591 --> 36:35.793
Society operates the
way society should.

36:35.794 --> 36:39.464
But on the other hand, many
ways this is a new country.

36:39.465 --> 36:40.731
It is.

36:40.732 --> 36:41.999
It's 19 years old.

36:42.000 --> 36:43.568
I think the Africans from the

36:43.569 --> 36:47.438
other countries see South
Africa as a place of hope.

